        lesson("rec-02", "Understand recovery", "Cues can trigger learned urgency", "Places, people, emotions, and routines can become linked with use. A craving can be intense without being an instruction.", "Name the cue, change location, delay action, and contact support.", "NIDA · Science of addiction", "https://nida.nih.gov/publications/drugs-brains-behavior-science-addiction/preface"),
        lesson("rec-03", "Understand recovery", "Treatment must fit the person", "No single treatment is appropriate for everyone. Substance, medical risk, mental health, housing, relationships, culture, and personal goals all affect the plan.", "Ask which level of care and evidence-based options match your current risks.", "NIDA · Treatment principles", "https://nida.nih.gov/publications/principles-drug-addiction-treatment-research-based-guide-third-edition/principles-effective-treatment"),
        lesson("rec-04", "Safety first", "Withdrawal can require medical care", "Withdrawal from alcohol, benzodiazepines, and some other substances can be dangerous. Do not assume that stopping suddenly is always safe.", "Contact a medical professional or treatment service before attempting a risky withdrawal alone.", "SAMHSA · Find treatment", "https://findtreatment.gov/"),
        lesson("rec-05", "Safety first", "Tolerance can fall", "After abstinence or reduced use, a previously tolerated opioid amount can cause overdose. Mixing substances can further increase risk.", "Avoid using alone, carry naloxone where relevant, and learn local overdose response.", "CDC · Overdose prevention", "https://www.cdc.gov/overdose-prevention/about/index.html"),
        lesson("rec-06", "Safety first", "Naloxone buys time", "Naloxone can reverse an opioid overdose temporarily. Emergency help is still needed because its effects can wear off before the opioid does.", "Learn where to obtain naloxone and show a trusted person how to use it.", "CDC · Lifesaving naloxone", "https://www.cdc.gov/stop-overdose/caring/naloxone.html"),
        lesson("rec-07", "Evidence-based care", "Medication can be treatment", "FDA-approved medications can be part of care for opioid, alcohol, and tobacco use disorders. Using medication for recovery is not replacing one moral failure with another.", "Ask a licensed prescriber which options, benefits, and risks apply to you.", "NIDA · Treatment", "https://nida.nih.gov/publications/drugs-brains-behavior-science-addiction/treatment-recovery"),
        lesson("rec-08", "Evidence-based care", "Skills and rewards can change behavior", "Behavioral treatments can help people recognize cues, build coping skills, strengthen recovery behaviors, and create meaningful alternatives.", "Choose one immediate, healthy reward for completing a protective action today.", "NIDA · Treatment", "https://nida.nih.gov/publications/drugs-brains-behavior-science-addiction/treatment-recovery"),
        lesson("rec-09", "Work with urges", "Delay creates options", "Urges change over time even when they do not disappear immediately. Creating distance reduces automatic access and gives support time to arrive.", "Set ten minutes, move away from access, and call or message someone safe.", "SAMHSA · Recovery support", "https://www.samhsa.gov/find-support"),
        lesson("rec-10", "Work with urges", "Environment is part of treatment", "Access, sleep loss, stress, money, isolation, and routines can raise risk. Recovery planning changes conditions instead of relying only on heroic refusal.", "Remove one cue and make one supportive action easier to reach.", "NIDA · Treatment principles", "https://nida.nih.gov/publications/principles-drug-addiction-treatment-research-based-guide-third-edition/principles-effective-treatment"),
        lesson("rec-11", "Long-term recovery", "A setback changes the plan", "A return to use can signal that treatment intensity, medication, environment, or support needs adjustment. Immediate safety comes before analysis.", "After safety is secured, record what happened in the hour before use without insults or excuses.", "SAMHSA · About recovery", "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/recovery/about"),
        lesson("rec-12", "Long-term recovery", "Community is one tool, not the whole system", "Peer groups can provide belonging and practical experience. They do not replace medical care, and no single recovery community fits everyone.", "Try one vetted support option and evaluate whether it increases safety, dignity, and follow-through.", "SAMHSA · Find support", "https://www.samhsa.gov/find-support"),
        lesson("rec-13", "Long-term recovery", "Co-occurring symptoms matter", "Anxiety, depression, trauma, pain, and substance use can interact. Integrated care is often more useful than asking which problem is the only real one.", "Tell a provider about both substance use and mental health symptoms as honestly as you can.", "SAMHSA · Co-occurring disorders", "https://www.samhsa.gov/co-occurring-disorders"),
        lesson("rec-14", "Long-term recovery", "Recovery can include more than abstinence", "Recovery may involve health, purpose, stable housing, relationships, medication, harm reduction, and community. Goals should still address immediate safety clearly.", "Name one recovery gain that is not simply a number of days.", "SAMHSA · About recovery", "https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/recovery/about"),
    ]

    private static let relationships = [
        lesson("rel-01", "Clear communication", "Observation is not accusation", "Conflict escalates when an interpretation is presented as a fact. Specific observable behavior creates more room for a useful response.", "Describe what a camera could have recorded before naming your interpretation.", "NIMH · Psychotherapies", "https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/topics/psychotherapies"),
